    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "They seek counsel of and trust in Egypt instead of in God. Isa.",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And the plenty shall not be known in the land, by reason of that famine following, etc.] That is, before it would be over; otherwise the former plenty was in some measure known by the stores of provisions laid up in the seven years of it, and which were brought forth when the famine became very pressing; but by that time, and before the seven years of it were ended, there were no traces of the foregoing plenty to be observed: for it [shall be] very grievous; as it was both in Egypt and in all the countries round about.\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 90": "The Com. Ver., through oversight or in its passion for variety ( see on \" Matthew 25:46\"), translates by 'lest ye enter' in Mark and Luke. In the following clause it gives in Mark, 'the spirit truly is ready,' but in Matt. where the Greek has exactly the same words, it translates, the spirit indeed is willing , the word 'indeed' being used to translate the Greek word men , a particle which merely indicates that to its clause something else wil presently be brought in contrast; compare on Matthew 3:11 or Matthew 9:\n31. The same term is here used in Mark. Death was the legal punishment of blasphemy. (Leviticus 24:16) The Mishna requires (\"Sanh.\" v, 5) that where Numbers vote would condemn to death, the matter must be postponed to the next day, when after the night's reflection any of those who voted to condemn may change, but not contrariwise. If this rule existed in the traditional law at the time of our Lord, we can image the Sanhedrin evading it by construing that they had virtually voted to condemn Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` some time before, (John `[char_John_Ref]` 11:47-53) or that the meeting after dawn (Matthew 27:1) was virtual y another session, with a portion of night for reflection\u00e2\u20ac\u201dwhich would have been a device quite after their fashion. It is, however, probable, as Edersheim and Sch\u00c3\u00bcrer remark, that these were largely ideal regulations, expressing what the Rabbis thought ought to be done, and by no means strictly fol owed. IV. Matthew 26:67 f, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Spit Upon, Buffeted, And Mocked Mark 14:65, Luke 22:63-\n31. I. Matthew 27:11-",
    "Commentary Vol. 91": "The same term is here used in Mark. Death was [v_Lev_24_16] the legal punishment of blasphemy. (Leviticus 24:16) The `[object_Tabernacle_Heb_9]` Mishna requires (\"Sanh.\" v, 5) that where Numbers vote would condemn to death, the matter must be postponed to the next day, when after the night's reflection any of those who voted to condemn may change, but not contrariwise. If this rule existed in the traditional law at the time of our Lord, we can image the Sanhedrin evading it by [v_Jhn_11_47] [v_Jhn_11_48] [v_Jhn_11_49] [v_Jhn_11_50] [v_Jhn_11_51] [v_Jhn_11_52] [v_Jhn_11_53] construing that they had virtually voted to condemn Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` some time before, (John `[char_John_Ref]` 11:47-53) or [v_Mat_27_1] that the meeting after dawn (Matthew 27:1) was virtually another session, with a portion of night for reflection\u00e2\u20ac\u201dwhich would have been a device quite after their fashion. It is, however, probable, as Edersheim and Sch\u00c3\u00bcrer remark, that these were largely ideal regulations, expressing what the Rabbis thought ought to be done, and by no means strictly followed. [v_Mat_26_67] IV. Matthew 26:67 f, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Spit Upon, Buffeted, And Mocked [v_Mrk_14_65] Mark 14:65, Luke 22:63-\n31. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Tried By Pilate [v_Mrk_15_2] [v_Mrk_15_3] [v_Mrk_15_4] [v_Mrk_15_5] [v_Mrk_15_6] [v_Mrk_15_7] [v_Mrk_15_8] [v_Mrk_15_9] [v_Mrk_15_10] [v_Mrk_15_11] [v_Mrk_15_12] [v_Mrk_15_13] [v_Mrk_15_14] [v_Mrk_15_15] [v_Mrk_15_16] [v_Mrk_15_17] [v_Mrk_15_18] [v_Mrk_15_19] [v_Mrk_15_20] Found also in Mark 15:2-20, Luke 23:2-25, John `[char_John_Ref]` 18:28 to John `[char_John_Ref]` 19:",
