    "Unknown": "Thy companions; thy friends or assistants in the taking of him. Make a banquet of him, i.e. feed upon him. Or, for him, i.e. for joy that thou hast taken him. Shall they part him among the merchants? as is usual in such cases, that all who are partners in the labour amid hazard may partake of the profit also, and divide the spoil.\nVer.",
    "Arthur W. Pink": "It shows us that a devil is to be expected among the servants of God . It was thus when Christ was here on earth; it is so still. Scripture warns us plainly against \u201cfalse prophets,\u201d and \u201cfalse apostles\u201d who are \u201cthe ministers of Satan.\u201d And the case of Judas gives point to these warnings. Whoever would have expected to find a \u201cdevil\u201d among the twelve! Whoever would have dreamed of finding a Judas among the apostles chosen by Christ Himself! But there was. And this is a solemn warning to us to place confidence in no man.",
    "Warren W. Wiersbe": "David\u2019s statement \u201cBehold, here am I\u201d reminds us of Abraham (Gen. 22:1 [c_Gen_22] [v_Gen_22_1] , 11), Jacob (Gen. 31:11 [c_Gen_31] [v_Gen_31_11] ; 46:2), Moses (Ex. 3:4 [c_Exo_3] [v_Exo_3_4] ), Samuel (1 Sam. 3:4 [c_1Sa_3] [v_1Sa_3_4] , 16), and Isaiah (Isa. 6:8 [c_Isa_6] [v_Isa_6_8] ). It is a statement of surrender.\n6. The Metropolitan Tabernacle Pulpit, vol. 24,",
    "William MacDonald": "). He cannot enter the inner court. The people are to stand behind the prince and worship as the priests sacrifice. Neither the prince nor the people can enter the inner court. In the Millennium, Israel will see Christ in the offerings, something the nation as a whole never did in the past. 46:9, 10 The people are to leave the outer court by the opposite gate to which they entered. They were to follow the movements of the prince. 46:11-18 In\nverses 11 and 12, the prince's freewill offerings are described; in\nverses 13-15, the daily sacrifices. Laws with respect to the prince's property prevent him from losing it permanently or from adding to it unjustly. 46:19-24 Kitchens are provided for the priests and for the people. D. The Millennial Land (Chaps. 47, 48)\nv. 6), and for Judah (",
    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "The `[group_Canaanites_Gen_10]` people were unfit for their Messiah, but will be judged in view of His coming glory: a remnant is acknowledged. Isa.",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "Williams (premillennial): Leviathan is a crocodile.\n6. Williams (premillennial): Leviathan is a crocodile.",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And, behold, seven thin ears, and blasted with the east wind, etc.] Which is very fatal to corn, to dry, burn, smite, or blast it; and especially to the corn in Egypt, whither it blew from the desert of Arabia: these 691 sprung up after them; after the seven full ears, in the same place the other did, or near unto them.\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 90": "Scrupulosity and injustice. (1) They would pay the price, but would not put the price of blood in the treasury. (2) They would not enter the governor's abode for fear of defilement, (John `[char_John_Ref]` 18:28) but they would manoeuvre and lie to make the governor murder the righteous. (3) They were horror-struck at a claim to be the Messiah, (Matthew 26:65 f.) and they would bribe Roman soldiers to a false report to prevent the claim from being believed. (Matthew 28:12) Matthew 27:",
    "Commentary Vol. 91": "Homiletical And Practical [v_Mat_27_3] Matthew 27:\n6. Scrupulosity and injustice. (1) They would pay the price, but would not put the price of blood in the treasury. (2) They would not enter the governor's abode for fear of defilement, (John `[char_John_Ref]` 18:28) but they would manoeuvre and lie to make the governor murder the righteous. (3) They were [v_Mat_26_65] horror-struck at a claim to be the Messiah, (Matthew 26:65 f.) and they would bribe Roman soldiers [v_Mat_28_12] to a false report to prevent the claim from being believed. (Matthew 28:12) [v_Mat_27_10] Matthew 27:"
